Game theory is the study of how and why people make decisions.
Lamarckism is an hypothesis regarding evolution.
Darwinism is a term used to talk about ideas connected to those Charles Darwin had about evolution.
In chemistry and physics, the atomic theory explains how our understanding of the atom has changed over time.
Reductionism is the idea that a system can be totally determined by looking at its parts, and by combining these using rules such as logic.
Kinetic theory or kinetic theory of gases attempts to explain overall properties of gases, such as pressure, temperature, or volume, by considering their molecular composition and motion.
Supersymmetry is a theory that says that when the universe formed, the same number of theoretical "superparticles" were created.
Monetarism is the belief that the right way for a government to manage a country's economy is to control how much money it prints.
Gresham's law is commonly written: "Bad money drives out good."
Utopia is a name for an imaginary community or society with a perfect system of laws and politics.Sir Thomas More invented the word for his 1516 book Utopia.
The word "information" is used in many different ways.
Malthusianism is a set of ideas developed by Reverend Thomas Robert Malthus.
The Pauli exclusion principle refers to the fact that certain particles cannot be at the same place at the same time, with the same energy.
Isaac Newton is widely known as the father of dynamics, the study of motion.
Geocentrism is the belief that the Earth is fixed at the centre of the Universe.
Keynesian economics describes the economics theories of John Maynard Keynes.
The Germ theory of disease is a theory in biology.
The Uncertainty principle is also called the Heisenberg uncertainty principle.
